We've been even more agressive than Mike recently in our "the heck
with hosttable hosts" strategy.  However, we have very different goals
from him.

As you can see from the headers of this message, I sent this message
from monk.proteon.com, but the from: is only @proteon.com.  The name
proteon.com is an MX record, presently pointing at monk.proteon.com.
The goal is to completely hide our internal structure.  Whatever
machine(s) the proteon.com MX points to will have complete lists of
what machines to forward the mail to.  This way we don't have to
confuse people outside of Proteon as to what machine to send mail to a
person at.  Nor do we have to worry about people changing machines, or
creating mail loops in trying to forward when they do so.

Unlike Mike's older configuration of user%realhost@berkeley.edu, I
beleive I am legal since what is right of the @ is a valid MX.  If
berkeley.edu was not a MX, only a CNAME, then that was a problem.

